29 Oct 2015 Spain: Guinean tested for Ebola in La Coruna
http://www.euroweeklynews.com/3.0.15/news/on-euro-weekly-news/spain-news-in-english/134636-man-tested-for-ebola-in-la-coru%C3%B1a
[The Galicia regional health authority released information on the afternoon of 28 Oct 2015 indicating that the 1st Ebola virus disease (EVD) test carried out on a 24-year-old man from Guinea had come back negative and a 2nd test will be submitted on 29 Oct 2015. The patient, who reached Lisbon from Guinea on 24 Oct 2015, traveled to La Coruna by road, reported to the casualty department of the University Hospital in La Coruna displaying worrying symptoms (fever, vomiting and diarrhea). He was taken, in a sealed unit, to Meixoeiro Hospital in Vigo where he was tested. The results of the 2nd test were negative on 29 Oct 2015 (Spanish language report).]

Research
-----
1 Nov 2015 MSF Switzerland: Undercounting of Ebola cases
[Ref: Gignoux E, Idowu R, Bawo L, Hurum L, Sprecher A, Bastard, et al. Use of capture-recapture to estimate underreporting of Ebola virus disease [letter]. Emerg Infect Dis. 2015 Dec [Accessed 1 Nov 2015]. http://dx.doi.org/10.3201/eid2112.150756]

31 Oct 2015 UK: MoD test lifespan of Ebola and plague using spider web
http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/MoD-test-lifespan-deadly-diseases-ebola-black/story-28085661-detail/story.html
[Scientists have come up with a way to work out if a battlefield or terrorist site, where biological weapons have been used, is safe to go back to -- using spider webs. Under strict conditions, scientists based at the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory are encouraging spiders to spin ultra-fine webs along a frame, which is then doused in deadly bacteria. They then put the frame in a special container and, because the web does not absorb the deadly micro-organism, such as the Ebola virus or the plague bacterium, the scientists can change atmospheric conditions in a bid to see how long it takes them to die. These condition changes -- temperature, humidity, or light for example -- can then be used to mimic how such conditions affect the persistence and survival of infectious aerosols in the outside environment.]

